Q: "What is the difference between Array and LinkedList?"
A: "
Array:
- Contiguous memory allocation
- O(1) random access (by index)
- O(n) insertion/deletion (shifting required)
- Fixed size (in static arrays)
- Better cache locality (faster for iteration)

LinkedList:
- Non-contiguous nodes connected by pointers
- O(n) random access (traverse from head)
- O(1) insertion/deletion (if position known)
- Dynamic size
- Extra memory for pointers

I'd use Array for frequent lookups and LinkedList for frequent 
insertions/deletions."

Q: "What is a HashMap? Where did you use it?"
A: "A HashMap stores key-value pairs with O(1) average time for 
get, put, and delete operations. Internally it uses hashing — the 
key is hashed to compute an index in an array of buckets.

I used this exact concept in my SmartCart cart design:
  cartData = { 'productId': { 'size': quantity } }
This is essentially a nested HashMap — O(1) to add, update, or 
lookup any item. Much better than an array which would need O(n) 
search."

Q: "What is the time complexity of common sorting algorithms?"
A: "
Bubble Sort    — O(n^2) average, O(n) best (already sorted)
Selection Sort — O(n^2) always
Insertion Sort — O(n^2) average, O(n) best
Merge Sort     — O(n log n) always (stable)
Quick Sort     — O(n log n) average, O(n^2) worst (when pivot is bad)
Heap Sort      — O(n log n) always

For most practical cases, Quick Sort is fastest due to low constants 
and good cache locality. Java's Arrays.sort() uses Dual-Pivot 
Quicksort for primitives and TimSort for objects."


---------- DATABASE QUESTIONS ----------

Q: "You mentioned MySQL and MongoDB. What's the difference?"
A: "
MySQL (SQL/Relational):
- Tables with rows and columns
- Fixed schema (ALTER TABLE to change)
- ACID compliant (strong consistency)
- JOIN operations for related data
- Best for: structured data, transactions, banking

MongoDB (NoSQL/Document):
- Collections with JSON-like documents
- Flexible schema (fields can vary per document)
- Eventual consistency (but supports transactions)
- Embedded documents instead of JOINs
- Best for: flexible data, rapid development, e-commerce

In SmartCart, I chose MongoDB because product attributes vary 
(different sizes, categories, images) and the cart is naturally 
a nested object — both fit the document model perfectly."

Q: "What is normalization?"
A: "Normalization is organizing a database to reduce redundancy 
and dependency. Key normal forms:
- 1NF: Atomic values, no repeating groups
- 2NF: 1NF + no partial dependencies on composite keys
- 3NF: 2NF + no transitive dependencies
- BCNF: Every determinant is a candidate key

In practice, I sometimes DENORMALIZE for performance — in SmartCart, 
I embedded the cart inside the User document instead of a separate 
Cart table, because they're always accessed together. This reduces 
query count at the cost of some data duplication."

Q: "What are ACID properties?"
A: "ACID ensures reliable database transactions:
- Atomicity: Transaction is all-or-nothing (if one step fails, 
  everything rolls back)
- Consistency: Database moves from one valid state to another
- Isolation: Concurrent transactions don't interfere with each other
- Durability: Once committed, data survives crashes

Example from SmartCart: When a payment is verified, I update both 
the order (payment: true) and clear the user's cart. Both operations 
should succeed together — that's atomicity."


---------- WEB DEVELOPMENT QUESTIONS ----------

Q: "What is the difference between HTTP GET and POST?"
A: "
GET: Retrieves data, parameters in URL, idempotent (safe to repeat), 
     cacheable, limited data size (~2000 chars)
POST: Submits data, parameters in body, not idempotent, not cacheable, 
      no size limit

In SmartCart: GET /api/product/list fetches all products (read-only). 
POST /api/user/register creates a new user (modifies data)."

Q: "What is REST API?"
A: "REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style 
for designing networked APIs. Key principles:
1. STATELESS — each request contains all info needed (no server 
   sessions; I use JWT for this)
2. RESOURCE-BASED — URLs represent resources (/api/products, /api/users)
3. HTTP METHODS — GET (read), POST (create), PUT (update), DELETE (remove)
4. JSON FORMAT — data exchanged as JSON

My SmartCart has 18 REST endpoints following these principles."

Q: "What is the difference between CSS, Bootstrap, and Tailwind?"
A: "
CSS: Raw styling language — full control, but verbose for large projects
Bootstrap: Pre-built component library (buttons, grids, navbars) — 
           fast development but websites look similar
Tailwind: Utility-first CSS framework — classes like 'px-4 flex gap-2' 
          directly in HTML — fast development with full customization

I used Tailwind in SmartCart (utilities with custom design) and 
Styled Components in NxtWatch (CSS-in-JS for dynamic theming)."

Q: "What is DOM?"
A: "DOM (Document Object Model) is a tree representation of an HTML 
page in memory. JavaScript can manipulate this tree to change what 
the user sees. React uses a Virtual DOM — a lightweight copy of the 
real DOM. When state changes, React compares the new Virtual DOM 
with the old one (diffing algorithm), and only updates the parts 
that actually changed (reconciliation). This makes React fast."


