PART 2: DSA PATTERNS (The patterns behind LeetCode problems)
==========================================================


PATTERN 1: TWO POINTERS
---
Used for: Sorted array problems, pair-finding, palindrome checks.

Example: Find two numbers that sum to target in sorted array.
  int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;
  while (left < right) {
      int sum = arr[left] + arr[right];
      if (sum == target) return new int[]{left, right};
      else if (sum < target) left++;
      else right--;
  }
Time: O(n), Space: O(1)

WHEN TO USE: "Whenever I see 'sorted array' + 'find pair/triplet', 
I think Two Pointers."


PATTERN 2: SLIDING WINDOW
---
Used for: Subarray/substring problems with constraints.

Example: Maximum sum subarray of size k.
  int maxSum = 0, windowSum = 0;
  for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
      windowSum += arr[i];
      if (i >= k - 1) {
          maxSum = Math.max(maxSum, windowSum);
          windowSum -= arr[i - k + 1];
      }
  }
Time: O(n), Space: O(1)

WHEN TO USE: "Whenever I see 'contiguous subarray' or 'substring 
of length k', I think Sliding Window."


PATTERN 3: HASHMAP FREQUENCY
---
Used for: Counting, duplicates, anagrams, two-sum.

Example: Two Sum (LeetCode #1)
  HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
  for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
      int complement = target - nums[i];
      if (map.containsKey(complement)) 
          return new int[]{map.get(complement), i};
      map.put(nums[i], i);
  }
Time: O(n), Space: O(n)

WHEN TO USE: "Need O(1) lookup? HashMap. Need to count 
frequencies? HashMap. Need to find complement? HashMap."


PATTERN 4: BINARY SEARCH
---
Used for: Finding element in sorted data, finding boundaries.

  int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;
  while (left <= right) {
      int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;  // Avoid overflow
      if (arr[mid] == target) return mid;
      else if (arr[mid] < target) left = mid + 1;
      else right = mid - 1;
  }
Time: O(log n), Space: O(1)

WHEN TO USE: "Sorted data + search = Binary Search. Also useful 
for 'minimum/maximum value that satisfies a condition.'"


PATTERN 5: BFS / DFS (Tree & Graph Traversal)
---
BFS (Breadth-First): Level by level. Uses Queue.
  Queue<Node> queue = new LinkedList<>();
  queue.add(root);
  while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
      Node curr = queue.poll();
      process(curr);
      if (curr.left != null) queue.add(curr.left);
      if (curr.right != null) queue.add(curr.right);
  }

DFS (Depth-First): Go deep first. Uses Recursion/Stack.
  void dfs(Node node) {
      if (node == null) return;
      process(node);        // Pre-order
      dfs(node.left);
      dfs(node.right);
  }

WHEN TO USE: "BFS for shortest path, level-order problems. 
DFS for path-finding, backtracking, tree traversal."


PATTERN 6: DYNAMIC PROGRAMMING
---
Two steps: Find recurrence relation → Memoize overlapping subproblems.

Example: Fibonacci
  Recursive (O(2^n)): fib(n) = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2)
  DP with memoization (O(n)):
    int[] dp = new int[n+1];
    dp[0] = 0; dp[1] = 1;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++)
        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2];

Classic DP problems: Climbing Stairs, Coin Change, Longest 
Common Subsequence, 0/1 Knapsack.

WHEN TO USE: "If a problem has OPTIMAL SUBSTRUCTURE (optimal 
solution built from optimal sub-solutions) and OVERLAPPING 
SUBPROBLEMS (same subproblem solved multiple times), use DP."


